Supervised by:  Dave Pichardo, M.D. (( 747 ) 447-3855).
Recurrent colon adenocarcinoma, status-post R1 resection and IORT.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

I was asked by Dr. Walter's service to visit with Mr. Schrupp for postoperative education purposes.  Briefly, Mr. Schrupp is a very pleasant 57-year-old male from West, Iowa.
1.  November 2005 - taken for surgery for what was thought to be diverticulitis, but ultimately was found to be a T4 (perforated colon), N0, M0 sigmoid adenocarcinoma.
2.  2005 - given adjuvant FOLFOX chemotherapy which was overall tolerated well.
3.  February 2009 - developed a small-bowel obstruction which was thought to be related to adhesions.
4.  July 2009 - PET/CT-scan was performed for followup and showed increased FDG uptake in a mass at the aortic bifurcation.
5.  September 2009 - taken for surgical resection of the retroperitoneal mass and drainage.  Debulking was performed.  Thought to be consistent with an abscess, but final pathology ultimately showed that the retroperitoneal abscess contained metastatic adenocarcinoma consistent with colon cancer.
6.  October 2009 - CT-scan showed a large mass between the common iliac vessels and encasing the vessels.
7.  October 2009 - seen by Dr. Taylor Baird of Radiation Oncology and Dr. Walter of Colorectal Surgery.  The joint consensus was to have the patient return home and receive external-beam radiation treatment and concurrent radiosensitizer chemotherapy with ultimate plan for surgical resection with IORT.
8.  October 29, 2009 - December 9, 2009 - received Xeloda chemotherapy with concurrent radiation.  This was overall tolerated well.
9.  January 2010 - Repeat imaging showed negligible decrease in the retroperitoneal mass.  He was noted to have an elevated creatinine.
10.  January 12, 2010 - due to elevated creatinine, a right ureteral stent was placed.  Unable to place a left stent.  Ultimately had a left nephrostomy tube placed.
11.  January 18, 2010 - taken for surgical resection by Dr. Walter.  Per the operative note, the tumor was adherent to the mesentery of the small-bowel in the region of the previous anastomosis and was unable to be completely resected as it would require extensive reconstruction of the urinary tract.  It was debulked as much as possible and given IORT.  Surgical pathology from biopsy of the mesentery was consistent with a grade 3 adenocarcinoma with a colon primary.  The sigmoid mesentery biopsy was also consistent with grade 3 adenocarcinoma.  The aortic bifurcation posterior margin was positive for metastatic adenocarcinoma, and the aortic bifurcation biopsy was also consistent with grade 3 adenocarcinoma.
Mr. Schrupp is continuing to recover from surgery and was sitting up in bed during our consultation today.

